abstract = {Cite as Ainhoa Magrach, Francisco P. Molina and Ignasi Bartomeus (2021) Niche complementarity among pollinators increases community-level plant reproductive success, Peer Community Journal, 1:1. Correspondence ainhoa.magrach@bc3research.org Peer-review Peer reviewed and recommended by PCI Ecology, https://doi. Abstract Our understanding of how the structure of species interactions shapes natural communities has increased, particularly regarding plant-pollinator interactions. However, research linking pollinator diversity to reproductive success has focused on pairwise plant-pollinator interactions, largely overlooking community-level dynamics. Here, we present one of the erst empirical studies linking pollinator visitation to plant reproduction from a community-wide perspective. We use a well-replicated dataset encompassing 16 plant-pollinator networks and data on reproductive success for 19 plant species from Mediterranean shrub ecosystems. We end that statistical models including simple visitation metrics are suucient to explain the variability observed. However, a mecha-nistic understanding of how pollinator diversity aaects reproductive success requires additional information on network structure. Speciically, we end positive eeects of increasing complementarity in the plant species visited by diierent pollinators on plant reproductive success. Hence, maintaining communities with a diversity of species but also of functions is paramount to preserving plant diversity.},
